00:13:19,228 --> 00:13:20,349
Let me leave you with one question.

248
00:13:22,009 --> 00:13:22,849
Who do you want to grow up to be?

249
00:13:23,810 --> 00:13:24,050
Thank you.

250
00:13:35,269 --> 00:13:38,472
So, looks like we are doing kind of the same rant here.

251
00:13:41,314 --> 00:13:44,517
So, my rant is called Garbage In, Garbage Out.

252
00:13:47,779 --> 00:13:49,521
So, yeah, I'm a programmer.

253
00:13:50,061 --> 00:13:52,563
I might be putting myself in a bucket here.

254
00:13:55,226 --> 00:13:58,889
I take random designs and turn them into computer code.

255
00:13:59,775 --> 00:14:02,096
And you know what, computers don't process very well.

256
00:14:02,596 --> 00:14:05,437
Well, they don't process nonsense.

257
00:14:05,697 --> 00:14:07,998
They just don't care what you feed them with.

258
00:14:09,879 --> 00:14:12,500
So you might have heard of Charles Babbage,

259
00:14:12,700 --> 00:14:14,720
the father of the computer himself.

260
00:14:15,781 --> 00:14:16,341
Well, guess what?

261
00:14:16,381 --> 00:14:17,281
He knew about this.

262
00:14:17,702 --> 00:14:18,882
Somebody asked him once.

263
00:14:20,383 --> 00:14:23,804
Mr. Babbage, if you put into the machine wrong figures,

264
00:14:24,004 --> 00:14:25,625
will the right answers come out?

265
00:14:27,008 --> 00:14:32,252
I'm not able rightly to apprehend the kind of confusion of ideas that could provoke such a question.

266
00:14:35,155 --> 00:14:41,440
Well, at least I suppose that's how Charles talked, because that's so ancient that there's no recording of his voice.

267
00:14:42,180 --> 00:14:42,521
Like, 1864.

268
00:14:44,682 --> 00:14:48,065
So, some people still don't get it.

269
00:14:48,506 --> 00:14:50,667
I said, you said no French, sorry about that.

270
00:14:51,008 --> 00:14:51,808
Putain de merde.

271
00:14:53,930 --> 00:14:54,811
So here's an example.

272
00:14:56,384 --> 00:14:59,445
This is from the development of this week's title about being a top model.

273
00:14:59,545 --> 00:15:01,306
And yeah, I worked on pretty awesome games.

274
00:15:02,266 --> 00:15:06,808
We had a basic dialogue scripting system with some variables for a good measure.

275
00:15:07,708 --> 00:15:10,949
I remember telling the narrative designer to go easy with that system.

276
00:15:11,869 --> 00:15:15,010
We had no budget, no time to check for consistency.

277
00:15:16,031 --> 00:15:17,031
What do you think happened?

278
00:15:18,926 --> 00:15:20,426
We let our players two options.

279
00:15:20,766 --> 00:15:23,567
In the story, you wander around in luxurious gardens,

280
00:15:23,647 --> 00:15:26,247
and at some point, one dialogue lets you date the gardener.

281
00:15:26,887 --> 00:15:29,448
Because everybody loves romance involving gardeners.

282
00:15:30,948 --> 00:15:32,869
And there was another dude you could date later,

283
00:15:32,889 --> 00:15:35,709
a taxi driver that would drive you around to your model stuff.

284
00:15:35,729 --> 00:15:37,389
So that made a total of two choices.

285
00:15:38,910 --> 00:15:42,370
Two choices, thus two possible combinations for which

286
00:15:42,410 --> 00:15:43,751
we had dialogues authored.

287
00:15:44,271 --> 00:15:47,231
In the end, you could either be dating the gardener

288
00:15:47,511 --> 00:15:48,652
or dating the driver.

289
00:15:49,908 --> 00:15:50,729
We're covered, right?

290
00:15:52,129 --> 00:15:52,330
Right?

291
00:15:53,630 --> 00:15:53,970
Well, no.

292
00:15:54,491 --> 00:15:56,291
Provided with these options, the computer

293
00:15:56,331 --> 00:15:59,193
performs very advanced computations

294
00:15:59,333 --> 00:16:01,954
and deduces four possible outcomes.

295
00:16:02,975 --> 00:16:05,476
Granted, you can be dating the gardener or the driver,

296
00:16:05,496 --> 00:16:08,257
but you can also date nobody, or worse, be polygamous,

297
00:16:08,677 --> 00:16:11,459
because the computer just doesn't care about morality.

298
00:16:12,199 --> 00:16:12,319
So.

299
00:16:14,613 --> 00:16:16,855
We discovered that we were missing dialogues for this

300
00:16:16,915 --> 00:16:19,276
at the very last moment, the evening before uploading

301
00:16:19,316 --> 00:16:20,357
to certification.

302
00:16:21,037 --> 00:16:23,419
We had to patch during the night, fingers crossed,

303
00:16:23,439 --> 00:16:26,061
hoping we weren't breaking the entire game.

304
00:16:26,081 --> 00:16:28,882
So I just want to make up for this

305
00:16:28,902 --> 00:16:31,344
to my former colleague, Martin, if you hear me someday.

306
00:16:32,285 --> 00:16:34,506
Sorry, man, I know I oversimplified things.

307
00:16:34,966 --> 00:16:38,008
Six years after release, we had our first user review

308
00:16:38,048 --> 00:16:40,670
on Metacritic, and it appears to be from a total fan of yours

309
00:16:40,690 --> 00:16:42,211
so you rock, Martin.

310
00:16:43,773 --> 00:16:48,076
Here's another example, this time from the early stages

311
00:16:48,216 --> 00:16:49,837
of the development of Dishonored 2.

312
00:16:51,338 --> 00:16:52,499
So let's take a guard.

313
00:16:53,100 --> 00:16:55,821
He's called Michel because we call all our guards Michel.

314
00:16:57,843 --> 00:16:59,244
That's the way it is, don't ask me why.

315
00:16:59,624 --> 00:17:02,466
Michel is patrolling when suddenly

316
00:17:03,046 --> 00:17:04,567
a player enters his field of view.

317
00:17:05,895 --> 00:17:08,716
So at this point, Michel starts fighting for his life

318
00:17:08,876 --> 00:17:11,077
and calls for help from time to time.

319
00:17:11,737 --> 00:17:14,238
And during pre-production, we only had placeholder speech,

320
00:17:14,738 --> 00:17:17,439
so our guards barked, aperu, which is French for,

321
00:17:17,459 --> 00:17:18,160
let's have a drink.

322
00:17:21,621 --> 00:17:24,282
The goal of these barks is to bring other guards

323
00:17:24,462 --> 00:17:26,643
at hearing range to the fight, not to the bar.

324
00:17:27,363 --> 00:17:30,324
So let's say we have another Michel in a room nearby.

325
00:17:32,165 --> 00:17:33,925
The other Michel hears the call.

326
00:17:35,215 --> 00:17:37,757
and joins the fight, barking Apero in return.

327
00:17:38,918 --> 00:17:40,759
On paper, this looks fair and good.

328
00:17:41,299 --> 00:17:43,281
We agreed on this design, and I innocently

329
00:17:43,321 --> 00:17:46,423
proceeded to implement it without the shadow of a doubt.

330
00:17:47,264 --> 00:17:49,025
Now guess what happens when you stress

331
00:17:49,065 --> 00:17:51,647
the system with more guards, and the player vanishes right

332
00:17:51,707 --> 00:17:52,828
in the middle of that fest?

333
00:17:54,489 --> 00:17:55,430
Well, this is what happens.

334
00:17:55,590 --> 00:17:58,492
There's no sound, but they are shouting Apero, Apero, Apero

335
00:17:58,552 --> 00:17:58,893
forever.

336
00:18:03,055 --> 00:18:07,138
Because the computer just doesn't care about doing the same thing over and over again.

337
00:18:08,699 --> 00:18:09,819
So let me sum this up.

338
00:18:09,839 --> 00:18:11,540
So it's crystal clear for everybody here.

339
00:18:11,780 --> 00:18:16,683
If you take nonsense and put it in a computer, well, it just blows up plain and simple.

340
00:18:16,943 --> 00:18:22,386
It stops to respond or loops forever or crashes or worse, just pretends everything's fine

341
00:18:22,927 --> 00:18:25,288
until you find out that your save file is corrupted.

342
00:18:26,008 --> 00:18:27,809
So the outcome is rarely fun.

343
00:18:28,250 --> 00:18:29,450
That's the curse of our craft.

344
00:18:30,815 --> 00:18:33,938
My point is, often the germs of failure

345
00:18:33,958 --> 00:18:36,161
are already present right at the design phase.

346
00:18:36,902 --> 00:18:40,085
So we need to be consistent as early as possible.

347
00:18:40,626 --> 00:18:43,689
Also our responsibility as programmers in our buckets

348
00:18:44,230 --> 00:18:46,913
is to invest time in proper error checking

349
00:18:47,614 --> 00:18:50,657
to prevent nonsense creation in the first place.

350
00:18:50,817 --> 00:18:52,259
It's always best in the long run.

351
00:18:54,758 --> 00:18:58,021
So please, every time we fail at doing so,

352
00:18:58,081 --> 00:18:59,742
a programmer somewhere has to pay back

353
00:18:59,762 --> 00:19:01,183
with a small amount of time

354
00:19:01,584 --> 00:19:03,445
and a considerable amount of sanity.

355
00:19:05,046 --> 00:19:08,870
And if you don't do it for me, at least do it for Charles.

356
00:19:10,391 --> 00:19:11,151
Thank you for listening.

357
00:19:21,699 --> 00:19:25,540
Guns, shooting, cover systems, sniper AI, grenade throwing,

358
00:19:25,660 --> 00:19:29,161
enemy detection systems, damage systems, tactical planners,

359
00:19:29,301 --> 00:19:32,562
animation syncing to have realistic and gruesome kills,

360
00:19:32,942 --> 00:19:34,682
blood splatter effect systems.

361
00:19:35,462 --> 00:19:35,962
I'm done.

362
00:19:36,563 --> 00:19:39,923
I love working in AI, but I'm really sick of game AI

363
00:19:39,963 --> 00:19:42,524
having so much focus on combat and killing.

364
00:19:43,721 --> 00:19:46,225
And it's the same shit that we keep redoing in every game.

365
00:19:46,465 --> 00:19:49,911
Enemy AI is where their sole purpose is kill or be killed.

366
00:19:50,371 --> 00:19:53,496
Gameplay mechanics and verbs only focused on combat.

367
00:19:54,481 --> 00:19:59,364
The thing is, the only thing that evolves is us trying to make things look more realistic.

368
00:19:59,945 --> 00:20:04,487
And it's actually kind of disturbing because I've started to get JIRAs with full-on blood

369
00:20:04,527 --> 00:20:08,870
splatter reports showing me how we can make our kills even more accurate.

370
00:20:09,351 --> 00:20:14,434
So either my testers are equally getting bored, or there is a bigger issue at play here.

371
00:20:16,708 --> 00:20:19,310
Now, some of my personal favorite games from the past year

372
00:20:19,410 --> 00:20:21,391
tend to have minimal amounts of combat

373
00:20:21,451 --> 00:20:23,592
and focus a lot more on socialization.

374
00:20:23,972 --> 00:20:26,594
But on the flip side, I also really do love

375
00:20:26,654 --> 00:20:29,595
watching horror movies and action movies,

376
00:20:30,035 --> 00:20:32,457
which made me start to think, well, what's different?

377
00:20:32,877 --> 00:20:35,819
Why am I okay with watching movies with combat,

378
00:20:35,859 --> 00:20:38,000
but I really dislike combat-based games?

379
00:20:38,620 --> 00:20:41,101
Well, it comes down to the NPCs that we're developing

380
00:20:41,241 --> 00:20:43,643
and the gameplay interactions that we give to the player.

381
00:20:44,856 --> 00:20:46,778
Characters on TV have a lot of depth.

382
00:20:47,359 --> 00:20:49,241
They have conflict between each other.

383
00:20:49,381 --> 00:20:52,044
They have ups and downs and we really care about them

384
00:20:52,104 --> 00:20:53,665
as they progress through their stories.

385
00:20:54,166 --> 00:20:55,647
They fight, they love, they grow.

386
00:20:55,667 --> 00:20:56,829
We care when they get hurt

387
00:20:56,909 --> 00:20:58,911
and we cringe when they make bad decisions.

388
00:20:59,331 --> 00:21:01,734
But we can't actually do anything to help them

389
00:21:01,894 --> 00:21:02,574
because it's TV.

390
00:21:03,515 --> 00:21:07,919
Games, on the other hand, have this great opportunity because we can actually interact with them.

391
00:21:08,279 --> 00:21:12,202
But honestly, I rarely give a shit about any of the NPCs in our games.

392
00:21:12,543 --> 00:21:16,566
They're too simple. They're designed to either protect someone, kill someone,

393
00:21:16,866 --> 00:21:19,048
or roam around in a big city like a zombie.

394
00:21:20,129 --> 00:21:23,431
In short, our NPCs are lacking empathy and intelligence.

395
00:21:23,932 --> 00:21:27,435
And this is what makes us really care about characters in cinema and TV.

396
00:21:28,335 --> 00:21:30,557
I'm going to call this artificial intelligence.

397
00:21:32,609 --> 00:21:37,352
as I would like to see some actual real interaction, socialization, and memorable moments

398
00:21:37,732 --> 00:21:40,373
that I can experience with the NPCs in our games,

399
00:21:40,854 --> 00:21:44,035
from developing love and relationships to hate and jealousy.

400
00:21:44,516 --> 00:21:47,037
So here are a few examples for inspirations.

401
00:21:47,958 --> 00:21:51,720
First off, if no one actually mentions Facade, Prom Week, and Versu,

402
00:21:51,840 --> 00:21:56,522
at least once in every AI Summit, then GDC will totally crash and everything will go wrong.

403
00:21:57,282 --> 00:21:57,423
So...

404
00:21:58,302 --> 00:22:00,864
For those of you who are new to the AI Summit,

405
00:22:01,284 --> 00:22:03,025
you are going to see these games mentioned

406
00:22:03,125 --> 00:22:04,286
at least once every year.

407
00:22:04,806 --> 00:22:06,527
And the reason is because these games,

408
00:22:08,148 --> 00:22:10,690
these are great examples of social simulation games

409
00:22:10,710 --> 00:22:12,771
where the player's actions actually changes

410
00:22:12,871 --> 00:22:14,912
the relationships between the NPCs.

411
00:22:15,653 --> 00:22:20,538
Now what pisses me off though is that we haven't actually really progressed all that much since

412
00:22:20,618 --> 00:22:21,619
these games came out.

413
00:22:22,280 --> 00:22:27,866
What I wish is for AAA to please just copy paste one of your thousand combat systems

414
00:22:27,886 --> 00:22:33,111
that you've already developed and actually put some of your AI developers on some interesting

415
00:22:33,191 --> 00:22:34,352
socialization models.

416
00:22:34,713 --> 00:22:38,176
Because what was done in these games are fucking brilliant and I want to see more of them.

417
00:22:39,325 --> 00:22:41,387
Next off is Generic Shooter X.

418
00:22:42,167 --> 00:22:46,871
A friend of mine once told me that when he was working on one of these games, he wrote

419
00:22:46,911 --> 00:22:49,453
some really interesting barks for the characters.

420
00:22:49,993 --> 00:22:54,456
And basically, there's this rare moment where one of the NPCs is idling with his gun and

421
00:22:54,496 --> 00:22:57,599
he looks up into the sky and he goes, I hate my job.

422
00:22:58,319 --> 00:23:02,822
And then he basically starts saying, this goes against everything that I believe in.

423
00:23:03,022 --> 00:23:05,324
I'm only doing this for my family.

424
00:23:05,664 --> 00:23:07,165
And I was like, oh, that's really awesome.

425
00:23:07,205 --> 00:23:09,727
There's a great back story for one of these NPCs.

426
00:23:10,307 --> 00:23:11,148
But let me guess.

427
00:23:11,608 --> 00:23:14,410
There's nothing that I can do in this game except kill him, right?

428
00:23:14,850 --> 00:23:15,011
Yeah.

429
00:23:15,911 --> 00:23:17,972
Is there an actually family that I can go to?

430
00:23:18,012 --> 00:23:19,332
Can I help out his family?

431
00:23:19,672 --> 00:23:19,872
No.

432
00:23:20,493 --> 00:23:24,674
Can I convince him maybe to join me and stop doing this horrible job?

433
00:23:25,034 --> 00:23:25,274
No.

434
00:23:25,815 --> 00:23:31,276
Because he was programmed with just one generic enemy AI behavior and nothing will actually

435
00:23:31,316 --> 00:23:33,217
change anything he does, which is sad.

436
00:23:34,655 --> 00:23:39,940
Next, Shadows of Mordor was amazing, and I'm pretty sure everyone in this room has raved

437
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:41,662
about their Nemesis system.

438
00:23:42,262 --> 00:23:45,866
For once, we had a game that left us with NPCs worth remembering.

439
00:23:46,326 --> 00:23:51,230
The game celebrated my losses, and it made me hate these NPCs, which was amazing.

440
00:23:51,651 --> 00:23:54,133
I had an actual emotional connection to the enemies.

441
00:23:54,774 --> 00:23:58,656
Now what pisses me off here is that when this game came out, everyone was like,

442
00:23:58,996 --> 00:24:02,098
oh, we're totally going to make a better version of this, just wait and see.

443
00:24:02,638 --> 00:24:08,282
It's been two and a half fucking years and we haven't seen anybody actually build upon this amazing system.

444
00:24:08,862 --> 00:24:13,445
However, yesterday they did announce the sequel, so hopefully we will see a little bit more.

445
00:24:15,257 --> 00:24:18,177
On a happy note, finally, finally, last year,

446
00:24:18,437 --> 00:24:19,558
the last Guardian came out,

447
00:24:20,698 --> 00:24:22,758
and I have to say my interactions with Trico

448
00:24:22,838 --> 00:24:24,639
was one of my favorite AI moments ever.

449
00:24:25,099 --> 00:24:28,540
What I loved was that interacting with Trico

450
00:24:28,720 --> 00:24:30,020
was actually a pain in the ass

451
00:24:30,600 --> 00:24:32,740
compared to most companion AIs

452
00:24:32,800 --> 00:24:35,101
that do everything that I ask them to do.

453
00:24:35,801 --> 00:24:37,622
It felt like training an actual animal,

454
00:24:37,762 --> 00:24:40,282
which made the AI feel so much more believable.

455
00:24:40,943 --> 00:24:45,111
I've probably never felt so attached to an AI character in a game because of its realistic,

456
00:24:45,191 --> 00:24:49,259
flawed, and loving behavior, so I hope that we develop more AIs like this.

457
00:24:50,326 --> 00:24:55,107
And finally, everyone in this room, if you're involved in AI, you should be watching Westworld.

458
00:24:56,207 --> 00:24:59,748
It has been one of my favorite television shows in the last year, and basically in the

459
00:24:59,788 --> 00:25:01,868
second episode, there's this beautiful quote.

460
00:25:02,628 --> 00:25:07,489
Anthony Hopkins says, it's not about giving the gamer what you think they want, the killing,

461
00:25:07,589 --> 00:25:08,530
the garish things.

462
00:25:08,930 --> 00:25:10,450
The players don't actually want that.

463
00:25:10,870 --> 00:25:14,931
They come back to the game for the subtleties, the details, that they imagine no one has

464
00:25:14,991 --> 00:25:17,591
noticed before, something that they've fallen in love with.

465
00:25:18,012 --> 00:25:21,114
They're not looking for a story that tells them who they are.

466
00:25:21,214 --> 00:25:22,375
They already know who they are.

467
00:25:22,695 --> 00:25:25,577
They're here because they want a glimpse of who they could become.

468
00:25:26,317 --> 00:25:30,681
And I love this moment because to me it represents everything that I wish that we were doing

469
00:25:30,721 --> 00:25:31,701
with our games.

470
00:25:32,222 --> 00:25:36,745
Actually having meaningful interactions with the NPCs, not just through violence.

471
00:25:37,697 --> 00:25:40,879
So, in conclusion, what do I want to see more of in our games?

472
00:25:41,259 --> 00:25:45,641
I want to work on the empathetic side of AI, on artificial intelligence.

473
00:25:45,841 --> 00:25:48,163
I want to actually care about the characters in our games.

474
00:25:48,623 --> 00:25:52,585
I want to find new ways of interacting with our games instead of new ways of hurting each other.

475
00:25:53,105 --> 00:25:57,488
Combat and violence is easy, we've been doing this years, and honestly it kind of feels cheap

476
00:25:57,588 --> 00:26:00,009
when you throw this into your game because we know it works.

477
00:26:00,569 --> 00:26:05,295
So please, let's invest more time instead into finding new and interesting mechanics,

478
00:26:05,375 --> 00:26:09,600
tools, systems, and AI to make games that feel new, innovative, and optimistic.

479
00:26:09,921 --> 00:26:10,241
Thank you.

480
00:26:19,913 --> 00:26:20,293
Hi, everyone.

481
00:26:21,659 --> 00:26:25,122
So my name's Rez, and I'm going to continue what appears to be this year's trend in terms

482
00:26:25,183 --> 00:26:27,785
of complaining about bad practices, basically.

