986
00:52:31,714 --> 00:52:33,375
and articles and message boards and Reddit

987
00:52:33,415 --> 00:52:35,956
and say, how do I put PCG in my game?

988
00:52:36,176 --> 00:52:37,656
How can I make a game that does this?

989
00:52:38,990 --> 00:52:40,832
Seriously, just, you know, stop.

990
00:52:41,793 --> 00:52:43,374
Academics, God, I love so many of you.

991
00:52:43,394 --> 00:52:44,575
You're so many of my great friends,

992
00:52:44,635 --> 00:52:47,717
and you do amazing work, but stop researching PCG.

993
00:52:48,438 --> 00:52:50,219
Just seriously, stop tormenting yourself,

994
00:52:50,279 --> 00:52:51,500
enslaving your grad students,

995
00:52:51,560 --> 00:52:53,422
and chasing the whole EP value

996
00:52:53,762 --> 00:52:57,545
in the name of academic research about PCG.

997
00:52:57,965 --> 00:53:02,309
All of you, just stop doing all of those things,

998
00:53:03,010 --> 00:53:06,692
and instead, just do the damn procedural content already.

999
00:53:07,590 --> 00:53:08,431
No, I'm serious!

1000
00:53:09,531 --> 00:53:14,033
By way of anecdote, I just came off a contract where I was working for a company called Pixelmage

1001
00:53:14,073 --> 00:53:16,654
Games on a game called Hero's Song.

1002
00:53:17,394 --> 00:53:21,356
We made it to Steam Early Access, had to pull it because of some business concerns and whatnot,

1003
00:53:21,416 --> 00:53:25,338
but it did see the light of day for a while there.

1004
00:53:25,858 --> 00:53:29,860
And the thing was, a massive amount of the game was PCG.

1005
00:53:30,440 --> 00:53:31,040
For example...

1006
00:53:32,121 --> 00:53:32,461
Big breath...

1007
00:53:33,227 --> 00:53:38,333
We did procedural world gen where we made continents and had many different biomes with rivers and lakes.

1008
00:53:38,594 --> 00:53:42,458
And we did it through the generation of tectonic plates that moved and created elevations.

1009
00:53:42,478 --> 00:53:46,584
We had moisture levels and wind movement that blew things around that gave us those biomes.

1010
00:53:46,764 --> 00:53:51,310
And our worlds were massive, 10,000 square kilometers to generate a world.

1011
00:53:51,930 --> 00:53:54,632
I mean, they looked kind of like this, and every single one was different.

1012
00:53:54,672 --> 00:53:55,592
They were really cool.

1013
00:53:55,632 --> 00:53:57,834
You could say, oh, look at this, this valley here.

1014
00:53:58,414 --> 00:54:00,395
We did procedural terrain across that.

1015
00:54:00,435 --> 00:54:05,998
We had grass and rocks and dirt and trees and all sorts of things, even flowers lettered

1016
00:54:06,038 --> 00:54:06,578
around the world.

1017
00:54:06,798 --> 00:54:08,739
And that was all based on whatever biome you were in.

1018
00:54:08,780 --> 00:54:12,762
We could actually even blend between biomes as you walked across the world, gradually

1019
00:54:12,802 --> 00:54:16,744
transitioning from grassland to plains to forest to mountains.

1020
00:54:17,544 --> 00:54:20,447
procedural civilization placement in those worlds

1021
00:54:20,767 --> 00:54:24,911
that the civilizations had capitals and cities and towns and villages and even

1022
00:54:25,011 --> 00:54:25,732
small camps

1023
00:54:26,132 --> 00:54:29,575
littered about the place. And we had hundreds of them in those worlds

1024
00:54:29,915 --> 00:54:33,539
and it was all based on the size of the civilization. What kind of coverage were

1025
00:54:33,559 --> 00:54:35,941
they? Were they a global civilization or were they just regional?

1026
00:54:36,741 --> 00:54:38,742
What preferences did they have for biomes?

1027
00:54:38,762 --> 00:54:41,462
Because the dwarves were in the mountains and the elves were in the forests

1028
00:54:41,542 --> 00:54:43,523
and the goblins were over here.

1029
00:54:44,723 --> 00:54:45,864
Land feature preferences.

1030
00:54:45,944 --> 00:54:49,945
Did they want to live next to lakes and rivers or along coasts or out in the middle of nowhere?

1031
00:54:50,485 --> 00:54:53,005
And what kind of neighbors did they prefer to live next to?

1032
00:54:53,085 --> 00:54:56,386
That all factored into where we placed civilizations in our world.

1033
00:54:56,406 --> 00:54:58,087
And so you can actually look at the map and see all these little...

1034
00:54:58,247 --> 00:54:59,467
This is my debug map, by the way.

1035
00:55:00,007 --> 00:55:04,310
All the little colored dots of, hey, look, those are cities and towns and villages and everything,

1036
00:55:04,350 --> 00:55:06,371
and these guys are over here and these are over there.

1037
00:55:06,811 --> 00:55:10,353
We did procedural history generation on these civilizations,

1038
00:55:10,633 --> 00:55:14,436
where we could have wars and assassinations and alliances and trading pacts

1039
00:55:14,776 --> 00:55:18,438
and creation of epic items and loss of epic items.

1040
00:55:18,478 --> 00:55:20,019
That is important, by the way.

1041
00:55:21,180 --> 00:55:23,741
And this was all based on proximity to the habitations,

1042
00:55:23,781 --> 00:55:25,962
the friendliness of the civilizations to each other,

1043
00:55:26,242 --> 00:55:28,904
the ebb and flow of relationships over time.

1044
00:55:29,144 --> 00:55:34,770
And speaking of time, we simulated 10,000 years of history when you generated your world.

1045
00:55:35,010 --> 00:55:36,131
Where's Tarn? Are you here?

1046
00:55:37,352 --> 00:55:39,234
Tarn Adams, I love you brother.

1047
00:55:39,674 --> 00:55:40,816
And no, we weren't copying your...

1048
00:55:41,036 --> 00:55:41,676
Okay, a little.

1049
00:55:43,940 --> 00:55:48,061
We did procedural road generation in those worlds, then, between the habitations and

1050
00:55:48,121 --> 00:55:52,102
even to points of interest in the world, like dungeons, so people could find them easier.

1051
00:55:52,403 --> 00:55:53,743
We had different sizes of roads.

1052
00:55:53,783 --> 00:55:57,144
Some of them were huge, between capitals like the King's Road, and some of them were just

1053
00:55:57,184 --> 00:55:59,984
paths going off to camps and dungeons and whatnot.

1054
00:56:00,425 --> 00:56:04,466
And those were, of course, based on the proximity, how close we were to these cities, what were

1055
00:56:04,486 --> 00:56:06,126
the friendliness of the civilizations.

1056
00:56:06,286 --> 00:56:10,107
Allies had roads running between them, not so much to your enemies, because that's dangerous.

1057
00:56:11,568 --> 00:56:13,710
And then of course we used the biome traversal costs.

1058
00:56:13,730 --> 00:56:16,452
You know, you don't want to run a road through the mountains unless you have to.

1059
00:56:17,753 --> 00:56:20,195
And then, so if you look carefully, you see the little black lines.

1060
00:56:20,215 --> 00:56:24,198
We had roads all over the place, networking across these massive worlds of ours.

1061
00:56:24,498 --> 00:56:26,139
The cities were procedurally generated.

1062
00:56:26,159 --> 00:56:28,041
We had all sorts of different types of buildings.

1063
00:56:28,081 --> 00:56:33,865
I think we had 25, 30 different types of buildings, and we placed them procedurally in a place

1064
00:56:33,885 --> 00:56:36,227
where we knew that there was going to be some sort of habitation.

1065
00:56:36,547 --> 00:56:43,073
And it was all based on the town size, the racial preferences for the types of buildings that would be in this racist city.

1066
00:56:43,914 --> 00:56:46,135
And then we had to work around the terrain features.

1067
00:56:46,175 --> 00:56:47,577
What if there's a river running through here?

1068
00:56:47,637 --> 00:56:50,139
We had to place them procedurally around the river.

1069
00:56:50,799 --> 00:56:53,562
The buildings and the dungeons themselves, the building shapes.

1070
00:56:53,602 --> 00:56:57,465
And yes, we actually had multi-story buildings that conformed to the exterior shape.

1071
00:56:58,145 --> 00:57:02,166
Building interiors were procedurally generated with the placement of objects in buildings.

1072
00:57:02,406 --> 00:57:06,747
The dungeon interiors were all procedurally generated. No dungeons were ever the same.

1073
00:57:07,087 --> 00:57:09,548
Not just modular rooms were gluing things together,

1074
00:57:09,768 --> 00:57:13,569
but they had nooks and crannies and obstacles and everything in the dungeons

1075
00:57:13,649 --> 00:57:17,289
so that they were all completely unique and you didn't know what was coming next.

1076
00:57:17,570 --> 00:57:18,730
But they looked real.

1077
00:57:19,030 --> 00:57:21,710
The population of the world was procedurally generated.

1078
00:57:21,970 --> 00:57:25,411
The creatures that were in it, the humanoid creatures as well as the animals.

1079
00:57:26,131 --> 00:57:27,011
Town inhabitants.

1080
00:57:27,372 --> 00:57:30,433
When we created those towns with those buildings, we staffed them.

1081
00:57:31,334 --> 00:57:34,835
Objects that were littered around the world, crafting items, loot, all sorts of

1082
00:57:34,895 --> 00:57:36,216
interesting things you could find.

1083
00:57:36,476 --> 00:57:38,357
And all of that was based on what biome

1084
00:57:38,697 --> 00:57:41,019
you were in. You would find different things in different places.

1085
00:57:41,279 --> 00:57:44,801
The influence of the civilization. While I'm in dwarf territory, therefore I'm

1086
00:57:44,821 --> 00:57:46,221
probably going to see a few more dwarfs.

1087
00:57:46,942 --> 00:57:51,285
And what the neighbors were, well, we're kind of near goblin territory and they might be invading.

1088
00:57:51,385 --> 00:57:52,546
Oh look, there are some.

1089
00:57:53,266 --> 00:57:58,010
And then the rarity, are they something that's common or a little bit uncommon, rare, or are they something unique?

1090
00:57:58,470 --> 00:58:03,574
And then we'd also space them out so that not all of the difficult stuff was right next to each other.

1091
00:58:03,834 --> 00:58:05,715
All procedurally at runtime.

1092
00:58:06,316 --> 00:58:11,782
Names. Everything in the world had a name, not just the characters and the cities, but geographic features.

1093
00:58:11,982 --> 00:58:17,828
You could have a forest that had a name, sometimes more than one, because different races called it different things.

1094
00:58:18,168 --> 00:58:25,516
Mountain ranges, etc. had names, and they were based on designer-created templates that we would sort out by race, sub-race, gender, whatever.

1095
00:58:25,536 --> 00:58:26,237
We could just...

1096
00:58:26,537 --> 00:58:31,423
like one example of that template right there, a prefix with the little apostrophe and first

1097
00:58:31,463 --> 00:58:35,207
and last and suffix, so you could have tens of millions of unique names, and just using

1098
00:58:35,267 --> 00:58:37,770
that template, for example, you could get things like this.

1099
00:58:39,272 --> 00:58:40,033
How do you even pronounce it?

1100
00:58:40,053 --> 00:58:40,213
A.I.

1101
00:58:40,233 --> 00:58:41,455
Dave Markmaster, A.I.

1102
00:58:41,575 --> 00:58:45,399
Steve Rabindude, and A.Lisha Ladeck, wow, what are the odds?

1103
00:58:46,558 --> 00:58:49,701
Cool. Anyway, procedural dialogue in this game.

1104
00:58:49,721 --> 00:58:52,623
Now, we had text instead of VO, so we could get away with a lot more here.

1105
00:58:52,943 --> 00:58:55,085
We had greetings, friendly, neutral, hostile, whatever.

1106
00:58:55,125 --> 00:58:56,846
We had taunts. We had barks.

1107
00:58:56,886 --> 00:58:59,408
We had information about the world that the characters would say,

1108
00:58:59,468 --> 00:59:01,089
not only to you, but to each other.

1109
00:59:01,349 --> 00:59:05,432
And you could hear worldwide information, regional information about the town,

1110
00:59:05,472 --> 00:59:07,774
or even just local dynamic events that were happening.

1111
00:59:07,814 --> 00:59:09,255
They may just tell you about it.

1112
00:59:10,342 --> 00:59:12,703
Some of it was generic, a lot of it was racially specific.

1113
00:59:13,223 --> 00:59:16,045
They sounded like that particular race.

1114
00:59:16,105 --> 00:59:18,046
They had their own speech patterns, et cetera.

1115
00:59:18,427 --> 00:59:19,787
And we used templates to create these

1116
00:59:19,827 --> 00:59:21,208
so that they could insert information

1117
00:59:21,268 --> 00:59:22,789
like race, gender, name, class.

1118
00:59:22,809 --> 00:59:23,870
They might call you by name,

1119
00:59:23,910 --> 00:59:26,151
they might call you by, refer to your race,

1120
00:59:26,211 --> 00:59:28,533
they might refer to each other by their class, whatever.

1121
00:59:28,753 --> 00:59:30,574
And we filtered it by all of the above,

1122
00:59:30,634 --> 00:59:31,815
including the disposition.

1123
00:59:32,135 --> 00:59:33,956
They're going to say completely different things to you

1124
00:59:34,036 --> 00:59:35,877
if you're hostile compared to friendly.

1125
00:59:37,308 --> 00:59:38,568
all filled into those templates.

1126
00:59:38,788 --> 00:59:40,629
Procedural information about the world

1127
00:59:40,649 --> 00:59:43,190
that was constantly being generated at runtime

1128
00:59:43,530 --> 00:59:45,290
using what was going on in the world

1129
00:59:45,570 --> 00:59:48,351
referenced by the generated names in the procedural dialogue

1130
00:59:48,591 --> 00:59:50,152
so you could actually hear things like,

1131
00:59:50,352 --> 00:59:52,932
we've heard reports of knolls to the southwest.

1132
00:59:52,972 --> 00:59:54,113
And if you went southwest,

1133
00:59:54,233 --> 00:59:55,613
damn it, you're gonna run into knolls.

1134
00:59:56,394 --> 00:59:59,958
They were telling you about this. There are goblins attacking the east

1135
01:00:00,178 --> 01:00:03,222
gate of the city. The orcs are massing in

1136
01:00:03,462 --> 01:00:07,687
the forest north of the river. They would fill in all of this information.

1137
01:00:10,052 --> 01:00:13,996
Items in the world, information about the items in the world, using the game world information

1138
01:00:14,036 --> 01:00:19,041
referred to by the names in the procedural dialogue with varying degrees of specificity.

1139
01:00:19,441 --> 01:00:20,582
What do I mean by that?

1140
01:00:21,123 --> 01:00:24,386
The magic tome of amazing AI is rumored to be lost far to the west.

1141
01:00:24,426 --> 01:00:26,108
Well, that's not terribly helpful, is it?

1142
01:00:26,589 --> 01:00:29,912
But as you get people who know more and more about this situation...

1143
01:00:30,492 --> 01:00:33,953
they would actually add more specificity to the point where you would get to

1144
01:00:33,993 --> 01:00:36,634
something along the lines of the magic tome of amazing AI

1145
01:00:36,914 --> 01:00:40,435
is lost far to the west in the dungeon of Moscone near the Californian city of

1146
01:00:40,475 --> 01:00:43,116
San Francisco where it is guarded by a horde of AI programmers

1147
01:00:43,476 --> 01:00:47,638
and that was the god-honest truth because they knew it was in the world

1148
01:00:47,718 --> 01:00:49,298
and they were signposting the player

1149
01:00:49,538 --> 01:00:52,319
hey there's something interesting over there in Moscone

1150
01:00:52,739 --> 01:00:54,740
and it's guarded by a lot of AI programmers

1151
01:00:55,600 --> 01:00:56,801
That was all procedural.

1152
01:00:56,961 --> 01:01:00,002
We even had quests, procedural quests that were constantly being generated

1153
01:01:00,122 --> 01:01:03,684
using the procedural items, placed in the procedural dungeons,

1154
01:01:03,764 --> 01:01:07,865
in the generated world, using the names and referenced by the dialogue.

1155
01:01:08,886 --> 01:01:12,908
So we had all of this stuff, all of this procedural.

1156
01:01:13,208 --> 01:01:16,409
I did a lot of it just by myself, and there was two or three others on the team

1157
01:01:16,429 --> 01:01:18,730
that worked on various portions of it.

1158
01:01:19,330 --> 01:01:21,611
My point is not necessarily to brag.

1159
01:01:21,671 --> 01:01:23,132
Okay, well, it was actually really kind of cool.

1160
01:01:25,234 --> 01:01:31,077
My point is this, we did all of this in one year.

1161
01:01:32,957 --> 01:01:34,518
And that's on top of me actually doing

1162
01:01:34,558 --> 01:01:36,379
the regular game AI that I had to do

1163
01:01:36,439 --> 01:01:38,920
for combat and for moving around and whatnot.

1164
01:01:38,960 --> 01:01:41,621
And by the way, all of the characters knew how to respond

1165
01:01:41,661 --> 01:01:45,083
to detect and process all of this procedural information.

1166
01:01:45,563 --> 01:01:46,363
How did we do this?

1167
01:01:47,975 --> 01:01:52,258
We didn't write a thesis, we didn't do years of research, no hand-wringing, no scouring blog posts,

1168
01:01:52,298 --> 01:01:53,799
or pleading for advice on forums.

1169
01:01:54,339 --> 01:01:56,721
We just looked at the problem one at a time,

1170
01:01:57,081 --> 01:01:58,522
we thought about it for a little bit,

1171
01:01:58,862 --> 01:02:00,623
and said, well, let's figure this out.

1172
01:02:01,143 --> 01:02:02,944
And then we just did it.

1173
01:02:03,405 --> 01:02:05,286
Because it's just programming.

1174
01:02:06,907 --> 01:02:09,888
So, again, I'm not here to brag about this.

1175
01:02:09,968 --> 01:02:11,569
There is a bigger message here.

1176
01:02:12,450 --> 01:02:14,591
I'm here to pump you up.

1177
01:02:15,493 --> 01:02:18,914
about the fact that, you know what, you can do this also.

1178
01:02:18,994 --> 01:02:21,916
You don't have, there is no such thing as an expert in PCG.

1179
01:02:23,576 --> 01:02:24,217
I'm serious.

1180
01:02:24,977 --> 01:02:28,618
Stop all of the hand-wringing and researching and just do it.

1181
01:02:30,139 --> 01:02:32,460
Because it might make things kind of better,

1182
01:02:32,580 --> 01:02:34,541
spraying some content around your games.

1183
01:02:35,821 --> 01:02:37,582
And if you still don't believe me,

1184
01:02:37,822 --> 01:02:42,124
if you still believe that you can't do it in your studios and in your games,

1185
01:02:43,725 --> 01:02:44,825
I know a guy might be able to help.

1186
01:02:46,871 --> 01:02:47,167
Thank you.

